('C2',3,'essay','literary_criticism','Write 4 sentences of sophisticated literary criticism.',NULL,'The novels achievement lies precisely in what it refuses: the consolations of resolution, the comfort of sympathetic characters, the reassurance of a stable narrative voice. What remains is more austere and more demanding: a prose that trusts the reader to dwell in difficulty. It is not a book that rewards impatience. Its pleasures, like its meanings, emerge only under the pressure of sustained attention.','Use sophisticated literary register.','consolation, austere, dwell, sustained.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','philosophical_argument','Argue a subtle philosophical claim (4 sentences).',NULL,'The very coherence of personal identity across time is, on closer inspection, harder to sustain than we suppose. What binds the child we were to the adult we have become is not any enduring substance but a continuity of narrative, itself always under revision. To the extent that we are anything stable, we are a story we tell ourselves, and retell. This is not a reduction but an illumination: we are authors as well as characters of the selves we live.','Use philosophical precision.','coherence, sustain, enduring, illumination.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','aphoristic_essay','Write 4 aphoristic sentences for an essay.',NULL,'The present is always the pasts unfinished sentence. We mistake familiarity for understanding; the two are seldom allies. What we call memory is less recovery than reconstruction, and reconstruction under pressure. The future has this advantage over the past: it permits us our illusions.','Craft aphoristic density.','compressed thought.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','rhetorical_speech','Compose 4 sentences of a rhetorical address.',NULL,'We gather today not to commemorate what has ended but to consecrate what is still beginning. We came here bearing grief; we must leave bearing resolve. We cannot undo what is done, but we can refuse to let it be the last word. Let our answer to this loss be a life worthier of what was lost.','Use rhetorical devices.','anaphora, antithesis.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','high_register','Write 4 sentences in elevated formal register.',NULL,'It is with considerable regret, and no little deliberation, that I find myself obliged to decline the invitation. The reasons are less a matter of principle than of practical necessity, though the distinction may be small consolation. Were circumstances different, my response would be, and would have been, otherwise. I trust that my absence will be received in the spirit it is offered.','Use elevated diction.','obliged, deliberation, consolation.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','nuanced_critique','Write a 4-sentence nuanced critique.',NULL,'The books ambition is both its strength and, paradoxically, its limit. What it attempts deserves admiration; what it achieves deserves scrutiny. Certain chapters move with real grace; others labour under the weight of their own claims. The final effect, for all that, is of a mind working seriously on questions that merit seriousness.','Balance critique with recognition.','ambition, labour, merit.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','oblique','Write 4 oblique, suggestive sentences.',NULL,'She did not answer, and in not answering answered everything. The room held, for a moment, the silence that follows what cannot be said. Later, she would describe the afternoon as uneventful, and perhaps, for her, it was. Some things, she had come to believe, were better left where they lay.','Use suggestive ambiguity.','indirection, suggestion.',120),
('C2',3,'essay','stylistic_virtuosity','Write 4 sentences demonstrating stylistic virtuosity.',NULL,'Dusk came, as dusk comes in that country, not gradually but all at once, and with it a silence older than the town itself. The olive trees, black now against the sky, stood as they had stood for centuries, patient and indifferent. From somewhere, a bell; from somewhere else, an answering bell, and then nothing. She remembered, then, why she had come, and why, perhaps, she would not leave.','Use stylistic range.','rhythm, repetition, evocation.',120),
